The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Nation at a Glance

 Kashmir rights chief resigns 

 Srinagar: The chairman of the state human rights commission resigned on Monday citing growing rights violations and accusing the government of not (being) serious about the commission, reports our correspondent.

 During my tenure, not even a single recommendation made by the commission has been implemented, Justice (retd) Ali Mohammad Mir said in his resignation letter to governor Lt Gen. (retd) S.K. Sinha.

 ir, who said he quit on grounds of conscience, added: Right from the day I assumed office, I have been observing that the government is not serious about the commission. I all along made strenuous efforts for drawing the attention of the government to the difficulties of the institution. The position has, however, worsened from day to day.

 Mir said because of this, the commission had failed to achieve its objectives and that he had been continuing in this post much against my conscience.

 Grenade strike on pilgrims

 New Delhi (PTI): At least 10 people, including seven pilgrims, were injured when militants hurled a grenade at a bus about to leave for the Baltal base camp to the Amarnath cave shrine from here on Monday. 

 The militants attacked the crowded bus at Batmaloo at around 3 pm, minutes before its departure for the base camp, 100 km from here. Twenty-five pilgrims, who had made bookings, were boarding the bus when the militants attacked, sources said. Three pedestrians were also injured. 

 No militant outfit has so far claimed responsibility for the incident. 

 Jessica probe

 new delhi (PTI): Delhi High Court has directed the special investigation team probing the Jessica Lal murder case to furnish a report within two months. 

 On the prosecutions plea for a fresh examination of the bullets found on the crime scene, the court said no purpose might be served by granting it.

 Sex racket case

 Srinagar (PTI): The CBI filed chargesheets on Monday against seven persons, including two former Jammu and Kashmir ministers, arrested in the sex racket case. Politicians and bureaucrats have been accused of pushing schoolgirls into the flesh trade.

 Salman warrant

 jodhpur (PTI): Rajasthan High Court has issued bailable warrants against actor Salman Khan and seven others in the Bhavad village poaching case. The state government had appealed for enhancing Salmans jail term. An unidentified object with protruding wires was found at Chennai domestic airport on Monday. The bomb disposal squad, however, identified it as a battery eliminator.




